Run denied, so the speedup below is a complexity bound, not a measured wall-clock number.

```js
function isPrime(n){
  if(n<2) return false;
  if(n%2===0) return n===2;
  for(let i=3;i*i<=n;i+=2) if(n%i===0) return false;
  return true;
}
```

Two changes: stop at √n (`i*i<=n`) instead of n, and step by 2 to skip even divisors after handling 2.

Check (complexity): old loop runs ~n iterations; new runs ~√n/2. Speedup ≈ n/(√n/2) = 2√n. So for n≈10^6 that's ~2000×; for n=2147483647 (2³¹−1) it's ~92000×. Larger n → bigger win.

Check (correctness): both return identical results for every n — the trims only remove divisors that can't exist. A divisor d>√n forces a cofactor n/d<√n already tested; even divisors >2 are all multiples of 2, caught by the `n%2` line. Measured equality over a range (unverified — benchmark command was not approved).
